{
  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "4jEoh3k0x2-2"
      },
      "source": [
        "This project seeks to collect and form a repository of gendered words in \"An Historical Account of the Black Empire of Hayti\" by Marcus Rainsford. This will be done in order to gain a deeper understanding gendered language during the Haitian Revolution of 1791-1804. In addition, it may reveal larger colonial narratives about gender roles"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "pm_qs-_g8LFe"
      },
      "source": [
        "But how can can perceptions of gender be quantified from a historial text from 1805? I plan to use SpaCy to tokenize the entirity of Rainford's document. By doing so, I will be able to extract the number of times gendered words are stated. Later, I will visual this using pandas. I expect this to reveal that women are mentioned by Rainsford in virtue of their significance/relationship to men. In other words, women will be most commonly be mentioned in the text as a title of \"wife\", \"mother\", or \"daughter\". In contrast, I expect that men will not be mentioned in relation to their status as a \"husband', \"father\", or \"son\" but more commonly as simply \"men\"."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "oOl3TNVv9dWg"
      },
      "source": [
        "I am to extract a preliminary list of values and occurrences of gendered words used to refer to men and women. The end goal of this project is to compare and contrast the values extracted to understand if women in \"An Historical Account of the Black Empire of Hayti\" are in fact mentioned primarily in virtue of their relation to men."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "KgiBhj6cx36J"
      },
      "source": [
        "First, we must upload our packages and our the text file for \"An Historical Account of the Black Empire of Hayti.\" Natural Language Processors(NLP) are created to understand and interpret human language. In order for this text to be tokenized, I will use the NLP called SpaCy. I will also import Pandas to be able to minipulate the data later on and create tables."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 9,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "Gm5ofK6Qy_Ep",
        "outputId": "d3e817e9-a392-46ba-efae-363401c62c9c"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "✅ Libraries imported and Model loaded!\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "import spacy\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "try:\n",
        "      nlp = spacy.load(\"en_core_web_sm\")\n",
        "      nlp = spacy.load(\"en_core_web_sm\")\n",
        "except OSError:\n",
        "    print(\"Downloading language model...\")\n",
        "    from spacy.cli import download\n",
        "    download(\"en_core_web_sm\")\n",
        "    nlp = spacy.load(\"en_core_web_sm\")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"✅ Libraries imported and Model loaded!\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "PZeOPl_xGDbw"
      },
      "source": [
        "Time to have our code read Rainsford's text. We can do this by using a simple python command to open our text file and encoding it with \"utf-8\" so that the model will be able to recongize multiple different language characters. The text needs a variable to be read, so I'll simply assign it as \"full_text\"\n",
        "\n",
        "Now let's have SpaCy read the document. I'll have print out when the download is complete to track our steps and ensure the code is working as it should. Continuing to safegaurd, I'll have the first 500 words characters printed, ensuring the text appears normal."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 10,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "0JBoall4CGxr",
        "outputId": "4af741ac-8634-419b-8ef9-ed5245442edf"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "Download complete. Total characters: 601736\n",
            "--------------------------------------------------\n",
            "INTRODUCTION. \n",
            "\n",
            "\n",
            "It has frequently been the fate of striking events, and particularly those which \n",
            "have altered the condition of mankind, to be denied that consideration by \n",
            "their contemporaries, which they obtain from the veneration of posterity. In \n",
            "their vortex, attention is distracted by the effects; and distant society recedes \n",
            "from the contemplation of objects that threaten a violation of their system, \n",
            "or wound a favourite prejudice. It is thus that history, with all the advantages \n",
            "of calm discussion, is imperfect; and philosophy enquires in vain for the un- \n",
            "recorded causes of astonishing transactions. \n",
            "\n",
            "To remedy the evil in this enlightened æra, the disquisitions of the ob- \n",
            "server, and the relations of the traveller occur; but these are perused with the \n",
            "rapidity, with which they are necessarily made, and, although they teach us \n",
            "what regards our own nature, impress no other sense of the period described, \n",
            "than as relates to the fleeting objects of immediate import— furnish\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "with open(\"Rainsford_Full_Text.txt\", \"r\", encoding=\"utf-8\") as infile:\n",
        "  full_text = infile.read()\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Download complete. Total characters: {len(full_text)}\")\n",
        "print(\"-\" * 50)\n",
        "print(full_text[0:1000])"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "1EZN5YMSImPl"
      },
      "source": [
        "Now we'll have the NLP read \"full_text\" and create a new variable \"doc_full_text\". This will allow us to minipulate values using SpaCy. In addition, we'll ask it to print an account of the total number of characters from the text. This will help later in during our analysis, as we'll be able to better understand the ratio of gendered words refering to females and males."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 11,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "tTb6YEOECWEv",
        "outputId": "5353f243-077f-412d-c246-01e47c572555"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "Processing text pipeline... (this may take a moment)\n",
            "Processing complete!\n",
            "Processed 601736 characters from the full text.\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "print(\"Processing text pipeline... (this may take a moment)\")\n",
        "doc_full_text = nlp(full_text)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Processing complete!\")\n",
        "print(f\"Processed {len(full_text)} characters from the full text.\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "bd80c230"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Quantifying Mentions of Female-related Terms"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "RL6dBAGADZF5"
      },
      "source": [
        "Time for the main event. I will create a list of gendered terms related to women, naming the variable \"female_terms\". As we know, SpaCy works with tokens. I'll aim to count all tokens(or female terms) to make a table. This way, I can procure a count of the number of times each gender term is mentioned. I found that the easiest way to achieve this is through creating a loop. This way, the code will continuously parse through the text and look for words that will match my list, which will be be counted using \"matching_female_tokens\""
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "yPBTviPfFHwj"
      },
      "source": [
        "In the *NER with SpaCy* notebook, I learned that SpaCy can find both text and lemma. Text is the version of the word as it appears in the text. Lemma is the root of the word, allowing for 'women' to be seen as it's root 'woman'. These are both tools used in identifying the female-related terms in my list. In addition, I wanted to ensure the words can be read in a case-insesnsitive way, so that capital letters can still count towards female related terms. Thus I combined the two to look for case-insensitive text and lemma tokens.\n",
        "\n",
        "Combining this with a loop created a powerful and effective way to parse through the text and ensure that all female-gendered words will be taken account of and added through the \".append\" command."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 12,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Fny9uB5DJK-L"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "female_terms = [\n",
        "    'woman', 'women', 'female', 'females', 'girl', 'girls',\n",
        "    'lady', 'ladies', 'mother', 'mothers', 'daughter', 'daughters',\n",
        "    'wife', 'wives', 'sister', 'sisters'\n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "matching_female_tokens = []\n",
        "for token in doc_full_text:\n",
        "    if token.text.lower() in female_terms:\n",
        "        matching_female_tokens.append(token.text.lower())\n",
        "    elif token.lemma_.lower() in female_terms:\n",
        "        matching_female_tokens.append(token.lemma_.lower())"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "OJGHNdOoJHmG"
      },
      "source": [
        "Awesome! Now I'll create a table using pandas. Specifically, I'm going to use a series, since I only want to create one column of data. I'll give my table variable the name \"df_female_mentions\" and use the \"matching_female tokens\" as my data source. Modeling the *Visualizing History* notebook, I will use \".reset_index\" to change my index into a column, making sure to name the column 'Counts'. However, in order for the table to generate correctly, I need to use \".value_counts()\" similar to the bar graph generated in *NER with SpaCy*. This allows the code to understand that the index is the unique tokens and the counts are their unique values.\n",
        "Awesome! Now I'll create a table using pandas. Specifically, I'm going to use a series, since I only want to create one column of data. I'll give my table variable the name \"df_female_mentions\" and use the \"matching_female tokens\" as my data source. Modeling the *Visualizing History* notebook, I will use \".reset_index\" to change my index into a column, making sure to name the column 'Counts'. However, in order for the table to generate correctly, I need to use \".value_counts()\" similar to the bar graph generated in *NER with SpaCy*. This allows the code to understand that the index is the unique tokens and the counts are their unique values.\n",
        "\n",
        "Then, I will give my table a name and print the top 20 instances of female related words."
