      "source": [
        "A preliminary observation, just by comparing the two graphs, displays an imbalance in the ways women and men are portrays in Rainford's text. Men are mentioned far more than women. Out of approximately 200 counts, 15 of male-related terms contained refrence to being a \"father(s)\" and 5 mentions to being a \"husband(s)\". This is in comparison to women who are mentioned approximately over half of the time as either \"mother(s)\" or \"wife(wives)\"\n",
        "A preliminary observation, just by comparing the two graphs, displays an imbalance in the ways women and men are portrays in Rainford's text. Men are mentioned far more than women. Out of approximately 200 counts, 15 of male-related terms contained refrence to being a \"father(s)\" and 5 mentions to being a \"husband(s)\". This is in comparison to women who are mentioned approximately over half of the time as either \"mother(s)\" or \"wife(wives)\"\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus far, my Minimum Viable Product is successful in demostrating code which addresses a specific historical inquiry on how women are documented in historical texts from the Haitian Revolution and Colonial Period in comparison to men. The code and data directly rely on one another to achieve this preliminary result, as the conversation about gender-norms and representation is aided with quantiative evidence. Working with \"An Historical Account of the Black Empire of Hayti\" would be tedidious if not for code to help identify and count specific instances of gendered langauge. Thus, my data and code work together to provide a mean to my end goal of comparing how women are portrayed in a primary historical source which has been used to inform the world of the Haitian Revolution."
